st, analyzes the ethical, legal, and social controversies surrounding each major technology and opens up a multitude of fascinating questions: Do frozen embryos have the right to be born? Should parents be allowed to select offspring traits? May a government force welfare recipients to take contraceptives? Robertson's arguments examine the broad range of consequences of each reproductive technology and offers a timely, multifaceted analysis of the competing interests at stake for patients, couples, doctors, policymakers, lawyers, and ethicists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAbortionxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aAbortion. 0aBioethics. 0aContraception Behavior. 0aContraceptionxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aHuman reproductive technologyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aReproductive technology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  aAdoption.  aAlpha fetal protein.  aAmbivalence.  aAmerican Fertility Society.  aAmniocentesis.  aAssisted reproduction.  aBaltimore school system.  aBladerunner scenario.  aCesarean section.  aChorion villus sampling.  aContraception.  aCopeland, Rhonda.  aCystic fibrosis.  aDuchenne’s muscular dystrophy.  aEisenstadt v. Baird.  aEnhancement of offspring.  aFetal surgery.  aFreedom of Choice Act.  aGestational surrogacy.  aGriswold v. Connecticut.  aHuman Genome Initiative.  aIn utero interventions.  aInfertility.  aKingdom, Elizabeth.  aMarshall, Thurgood.  aNational Institutes of Health.  aNorplant.  aOntario Law Reform Commission.  aOverpopulation.  aParkinson’s disease.  aPhenylketonuria.  aPhiladelphia Inquirer.  aProbation.  aRU486.  aRadin, Margaret.  aReproductive revolution.  aRothman, Barbara Katz.  aShakespeare, William.  aSickle cell anemia.  aSterilization.  aSullivan, Louis.  a